{"title_page": "Conservative Group for Europe", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox political youth organization\n|name = Conservative Group for Europe (CGE)\n|native_name =\n|colorcode = {{Conservative and Unionist Party (UK)/meta/color}}\n|logo = [[File:Conservative Europe Group (UK).jpg|300px|Conservative Group for Europe]]\n|chairperson = [[Dominic Grieve]]\n|president = [[Kenneth Clarke]]\n|vice president = [[Alistair Burt]] <small>(joint)</small><br>[[Richard Harrington (politician)|Richard Harrington]] <small>(joint)</small>\n|founded = 1969\n|website = [http://www.conservativegroupforeurope.org.uk www.conservativegroupforeurope.org.uk]\n}}\n\nThe '''Conservative Group for Europe (CGE)''' was founded in 1969 to promote the UK's entry to the [[European Economic Community]]. The organisation\u00a0is committed to a positive and constructive approach to the UK\u2019s relationship with the [[European Union]]. \n\nThe Group campaigned to remain in the EU during the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]]. Although the organisation accepts the UK\u2019s departure from the European Union it believes that it is in the bests interests of the UK, EU and wider world that the UK maintains a close relationship with the EU in the future. It is for this reason the CGE is resolutely opposed to a No-deal Brexit. <ref>{{cite web|title= DOMINIC GRIEVE: The rebels are the real voice of conservatism |url=https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/top-stories/dominic-grieve-on-being-expelled-by-boris-johnson-1-6276115 |website=theneweuropean.co.uk |publisher=The New European|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Rt Hon. [[Dominic Grieve]] QC is the current Chair, and the Rt Hon. [[Kenneth Clarke]] CH QC is the President. The two Vice Presidents are the Rt Hon. [[Alistair Burt]] and [[Richard Harrington (politician)|Richard Harrington]].<ref>{{cite web|title= People|url=https://www.conservativegroupforeurope.org.uk/people |website=conservativegroupforeurope.org.uk |publisher=Conservative Group for Europe|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Conservative Group for Europe was founded in 1969 under the Chairmanship of David Baker. The Group was originally called the European Forum and first Annual General Meeting was held just after Sir [[Edward Heath]]'s General Election victory in 1970. <ref>{{cite web|title= History|url=http://www.conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk/history|website=conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk|publisher=Conservative Europe Group|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith the resignation of French President [[Charles De Gaulle]] who was opposed the UK membership to the [[EEC]] and the election of pro-European Heath negotiations commenced for the UK to join the EEC.\nIt was during these negotiations that the Group changed its name to the Conservative Group for Europe (CGE).\n\nThe CGE played a vital role in the UK\u2019s ascension to the EEC. The Group brought together pro-European Conservatives and worked with like-minded parties in France to help secure UK\u2019s entry to the EEC on 1 January 1973.\n\nThe Conservative referendum campaign in 1975 for the UK to remain a member of the EEC was launched by the Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] addressing the Conservative Group for Europe. <ref>{{cite web|title= Speech to Conservative Group for Europe (opening Conservative referendum campaign)|url=https://www.margaretthatcher.org/document/102675|website=conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk|publisher=Margaret Thatcher Foundation|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980/90s its annual conference at Brandon Hall near Coventry attracted leading figures from the Conservative Party, MPs and MEPs and leaders from countries with which the Conservative Party was affiliated in the European Peoples Party.\n\nMany conservative politicans have been associated with the CGE, including Norman St John-Stevas, James Spicer,  Ian Taylor, Robert Walter, Neil Carmichael John Gummer (Lord Deben), Lord Brittan, Tom Spencer (former MEP), Sir Tony Baldry and David Curry. <ref>{{cite web|title= Long read: the Conservative Party\u2019s legacy on Europe|url= https://www.ukandeu.ac.uk/long-read-the-conservative-partys-legacy-on-europe/\n|website= ukandeu.ac.uk|publisher=The UK in a Changing Europe|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Current Role==\n\n==Membership==\nMembership of the CGE is open to anyone who supports Conservatives values and close relationship between the UK and the EU. Individuals who are either members of the Conservative Party or who are Independent Conservatives (not members of the Conservative Party, but ideologically centre-right and do not hold membership of any other political party) are permitted to join. <ref>{{cite web|title= Membership|url=http://www.conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk/membership|website=conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk|publisher=Conservative Europe Group|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe CGE has a large number of current and former Parliamentarians as members and Partons including former Prime Minister Sir [[John Major]] and Deputy Prime Minister [[Lord Heseltine]]. <ref>{{cite web|title= Who We Are|url=http://www.conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk/who-we-are|website=conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk|publisher=Conservative Europe Group|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of organisations associated with the Conservative Party (UK)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.conservativegroupforeurope.org.uk Official website]\n\n{{UK Conservative Party}}\n\n[[Category:1969 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:European Union\u2013related advocacy groups in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organisations associated with the Conservative Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:Politics of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Pro-Europeanism in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom and the European Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox political youth organization\n|name = Conservative Group for Europe (CGE)\n|native_name =\n|colorcode = {{Conservative and Unionist Party (UK)/meta/color}}\n|logo = [[File:Conservative Europe Group (UK).jpg|300px|Conservative Group for Europe]]\n|chairperson = [[Dominic Grieve]]\n|president = [[Kenneth Clarke]]\n|vice president = [[Alistair Burt]] <small>(joint)</small><br>[[Richard Harrington (politician)|Richard Harrington]] <small>(joint)</small>\n|founded = 1969\n|website = [http://www.conservativegroupforeurope.org.uk www.conservativegroupforeurope.org.uk]\n}}\n\nThe '''Conservative Group for Europe (CGE)''' was founded in 1969 to promote the UK's entry to the [[European Economic Community]]. The organisation\u00a0is committed to a positive and constructive approach to the UK\u2019s relationship with the [[European Union]]. \n\nThe Group campaigned to remain in the EU during the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]]. Although the organisation accepts the UK\u2019s departure from the European Union it believes that it is in the bests interests of the UK, EU and wider world that the UK maintains a close relationship with the EU in the future. It is for this reason the CGE is resolutely opposed to a No-deal Brexit. <ref>{{cite web|title= DOMINIC GRIEVE: The rebels are the real voice of conservatism |url=https://www.theneweuropean.co.uk/top-stories/dominic-grieve-on-being-expelled-by-boris-johnson-1-6276115 |website=theneweuropean.co.uk |publisher=The New European|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Rt Hon. [[Dominic Grieve]] QC is the current Chair, and the Rt Hon. [[Kenneth Clarke]] CH QC is the President. The two Vice Presidents are the Rt Hon. [[Alistair Burt]] and [[Richard Harrington (politician)|Richard Harrington]].<ref>{{cite web|title= People|url=https://www.conservativegroupforeurope.org.uk/people |website=conservativegroupforeurope.org.uk |publisher=Conservative Group for Europe|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Conservative Group for Europe was founded in 1969 under the Chairmanship of David Baker. The Group was originally called the European Forum and first Annual General Meeting was held just after Sir [[Edward Heath]]'s General Election victory in 1970. <ref>{{cite web|title= History|url=http://www.conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk/history|website=conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk|publisher=Conservative Europe Group|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith the resignation of French President [[Charles De Gaulle]] who was opposed the UK membership to the [[EEC]] and the election of pro-European Heath negotiations commenced for the UK to join the EEC.\nIt was during these negotiations that the Group changed its name to the Conservative Group for Europe (CGE).\n\nThe CGE played a vital role in the UK\u2019s ascension to the EEC. The Group brought together pro-European Conservatives and worked with like-minded parties in France to help secure UK\u2019s entry to the EEC on 1 January 1973.\n\nThe Conservative referendum campaign in 1975 for the UK to remain a member of the EEC was launched by the Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] addressing the Conservative Group for Europe. <ref>{{cite web|title= Speech to Conservative Group for Europe (opening Conservative referendum campaign)|url=https://www.margaretthatcher.org/document/102675|website=conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk|publisher=Margaret Thatcher Foundation|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980/90s its annual conference at Brandon Hall near Coventry attracted leading figures from the Conservative Party, MPs and MEPs and leaders from countries with which the Conservative Party was affiliated in the European Peoples Party.\n\nMany conservative politicans have been associated with the CGE, including Norman St John-Stevas, James Spicer,  Ian Taylor, Robert Walter, Neil Carmichael John Gummer (Lord Deben), Lord Brittan, Tom Spencer (former MEP), Sir Tony Baldry and David Curry. <ref>{{cite web|title= Long read: the Conservative Party\u2019s legacy on Europe|url= https://www.ukandeu.ac.uk/long-read-the-conservative-partys-legacy-on-europe/\n|website= ukandeu.ac.uk|publisher=The UK in a Changing Europe|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Membership==\nMembership of the CGE is open to anyone who supports Conservatives values and close relationship between the UK and the EU. Individuals who are either members of the Conservative Party or who are Independent Conservatives (not members of the Conservative Party, but ideologically centre-right and do not hold membership of any other political party) are permitted to join. <ref>{{cite web|title= Membership|url=http://www.conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk/membership|website=conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk|publisher=Conservative Europe Group|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe CGE has a large number of current and former Parliamentarians as members and Partons including former Prime Minister Sir [[John Major]] and Deputy Prime Minister [[Lord Heseltine]]. <ref>{{cite web|title= Who We Are|url=http://www.conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk/who-we-are|website=conservativeeuropegroup.org.uk|publisher=Conservative Europe Group|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of organisations associated with the Conservative Party (UK)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.conservativegroupforeurope.org.uk Official website]\n\n{{UK Conservative Party}}\n\n[[Category:1969 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:European Union\u2013related advocacy groups in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organisations associated with the Conservative Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:Politics of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Pro-Europeanis